{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775850780911,"sessionID":"ses_2870bf392ffeKZ8jL8UQ3Wxavm","part":{"id":"prt_d78f478c5001tzc5w2CCqBltUi","messageID":"msg_d78f448fa001eBkQbOFsCzcwIv","sessionID":"ses_2870bf392ffeKZ8jL8UQ3Wxavm","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-b68c44a93d34400cb6c6844c97dd9fb5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP 服务框架\n2: \n3: Module: `pkg/workloadmanager`  \n4: Language: Go  \n5: Size: M\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Overview\n10: \n11: Define the HTTP service framework for WorkloadManager, providing RESTful API infrastructure, middleware architecture, lifecycle management, health endpoints, and unified error handling.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## Requirements\n16: \n17: ### REQ-001: HTTPServer Configuration\n18: \n19: **GIVEN** the `server.go` file defines the HTTP server core implementation  \n20: **WHEN** a developer needs to configure and manage the HTTP server lifecycle  \n21: **THEN** `HTTPServer` struct and `Config` struct shall be available with proper fields and methods\n22: \n23: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n24: \n25: ```go\n26: // Scenario 1: HTTPServer struct definition\n27: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server.go\n28: WHEN reading the HTTPServer struct\n29: THEN it SHALL contain fields: server *http.Server, router chi.Router, config Config, handlers map[string]Handler, logger Logger, stopCh chan struct{}\n30: \n31: // Scenario 2: Config struct fields\n32: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/config.go\n33: WHEN reading the Config struct\n34: THEN it SHALL contain fields: Addr string, ReadTimeout time.Duration, WriteTimeout time.Duration, IdleTimeout time.Duration, ShutdownTimeout time.Duration, EnableHealthz bool, EnableReadyz bool\n35: \n36: // Scenario 3: DefaultConfig function\n37: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/config.go\n38: WHEN calling DefaultConfig()\n39: THEN it SHALL return Config with Addr \":8080\", ReadTimeout 15s, WriteTimeout 15s, IdleTimeout 60s, ShutdownTimeout 30s, EnableHealthz true, EnableReadyz true\n40: \n41: // Scenario 4: HTTPServer constructor\n42: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server.go\n43: WHEN calling NewHTTPServer(cfg Config, logger Logger)\n44: THEN it SHALL return *HTTPServer with router initialized using chi.NewRouter()\n45: ```\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ### REQ-002: HTTPServer Lifecycle Management\n50: \n51: **GIVEN** HTTPServer needs to support graceful startup and shutdown  \n52: **WHEN** managing the server lifecycle  \n53: **THEN** Start, Stop, and GracefulShutdown methods shall be properly implemented\n54: \n55: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n56: \n57: ```go\n58: // Scenario 1: HTTPServer.Start method\n59: GIVEN an HTTPServer instance with valid config\n60: WHEN calling Start()\n61: THEN it SHALL configure http.Server with timeouts from Config\n62: AND it SHALL start ListenAndServe on the configured address\n63: AND it SHALL return error channel for async error handling\n64: \n65: // Scenario 2: HTTPServer.Stop method\n66: GIVEN a running HTTPServer instance\n67: WHEN calling Stop(ctx context.Context)\n68: THEN it SHALL call http.Server.Shutdown(ctx)\n69: AND it SHALL wait for existing connections to complete within ShutdownTimeout\n70: AND it SHALL close stopCh to signal shutdown complete\n71: \n72: // Scenario 3: HTTPServer.GracefulShutdown method\n73: GIVEN a running HTTPServer instance\n74: WHEN calling GracefulShutdown()\n75: THEN it SHALL setup signal handler for SIGTERM and SIGINT\n76: AND it SHALL call Stop() on signal receipt\n77: \n78: // Scenario 4: Graceful shutdown with context timeout\n79: GIVEN an HTTPServer with ShutdownTimeout 30s\n80: WHEN graceful shutdown is triggered\n81: THEN existing connections SHALL complete within 30 seconds\n82: AND new connections SHALL be rejected after shutdown starts\n83: ```\n84: \n85: ---\n86: \n87: ### REQ-003: Router Implementation\n88: \n89: **GIVEN** the router needs to support route grouping and middleware scoping  \n90: **WHEN** configuring RESTful API routes  \n91: **THEN** Router struct wrapping chi.Router shall be properly defined\n92: \n93: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n94: \n95: ```go\n96: // Scenario 1: Router struct definition\n97: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/router.go\n98: WHEN reading the Router struct\n99: THEN it SHALL embed chi.Router\n100: \n101: // Scenario 2: NewRouter constructor\n102: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/router.go\n103: WHEN calling NewRouter()\n104: THEN it SHALL return *Router with chi.NewRouter() initialized\n105: \n106: // Scenario 3: RegisterHandlers method\n107: GIVEN a Router instance and multiple Handler implementations\n108: WHEN calling RegisterHandlers(handlers ...Handler)\n109: THEN each handler's Register method SHALL be called on the underlying chi.Router\n110: \n111: // Scenario 4: chi router dependency\n112: GIVEN go.mod\n113: WHEN reading dependencies\n114: THEN github.com/go-chi/chi/v5 SHALL be listed as a dependency\n115: ```\n116: \n117: ---\n118: \n119: ### REQ-004: Handler Interface\n120: \n121: **GIVEN** handlers need a common registration interface  \n122: **WHEN** implementing new API endpoint handlers  \n123: **THEN** Handler interface and HandlerFunc type shall be properly defined\n124: \n125: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n126: \n127: ```go\n128: // Scenario 1: Handler interface definition\n129: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/handler.go\n130: WHEN reading the Handler interface\n131: THEN it SHALL define Register(r chi.Router) method\n132: \n133: // Scenario 2: HandlerFunc type definition\n134: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/handler.go\n135: WHEN reading the HandlerFunc type\n136: THEN it SHALL be defined as type HandlerFunc func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) error\n137: \n138: // Scenario 3: HandlerFunc.ServeHTTP implementation\n139: GIVEN a HandlerFunc instance\n140: WHEN calling ServeHTTP(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request)\n141: THEN it SHALL call the HandlerFunc and handle errors via HandleError\n142: \n143: // Scenario 4: RegisterHandler method on HTTPServer\n144: GIVEN an HTTPServer instance\n145: WHEN calling RegisterHandler(name string, h Handler)\n146: THEN the handler SHALL be stored in handlers map\n147: AND it SHALL be registered on the router\n148: ```\n149: \n150: ---\n151: \n152: ### REQ-005: Health Handler Implementation\n153: \n154: **GIVEN** Kubernetes needs liveness and readiness probe endpoints  \n155: **WHEN** implementing health check endpoints  \n156: **THEN** HealthHandler with /healthz and /readyz shall be properly implemented\n157: \n158: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n159: \n160: ```go\n161: // Scenario 1: HealthHandler struct definition\n162: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go\n163: WHEN reading the HealthHandler struct\n164: THEN it SHALL contain checker HealthChecker field\n165: \n166: // Scenario 2: HealthChecker interface definition\n167: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go\n168: WHEN reading the HealthChecker interface\n169: THEN it SHALL define IsHealthy() bool and IsReady() bool methods\n170: \n171: // Scenario 3: NewHealthHandler constructor\n172: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go\n173: WHEN calling NewHealthHandler(checker HealthChecker)\n174: THEN it SHALL return *HealthHandler with checker field set\n175: \n176: // Scenario 4: healthz endpoint\n177: GIVEN a HealthHandler registered on router\n178: WHEN GET request is sent to /healthz\n179: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with JSON body {\"status\": \"ok\"}\n180: \n181: // Scenario 5: readyz endpoint with checker ready\n182: GIVEN a HealthHandler with checker where IsReady() returns true\n183: WHEN GET request is sent to /readyz\n184: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with JSON body {\"status\": \"ready\"}\n185: \n186: // Scenario 6: readyz endpoint with checker not ready\n187: GIVEN a HealthHandler with checker where IsReady() returns false\n188: WHEN GET request is sent to /readyz\n189: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 503 with JSON body {\"status\": \"not ready\"}\n190: \n191: // Scenario 7: readyz endpoint without checker\n192: GIVEN a HealthHandler with nil checker\n193: WHEN GET request is sent to /readyz\n194: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 503 with JSON body {\"status\": \"not ready\"}\n195: ```\n196: \n197: ---\n198: \n199: ### REQ-006: Logging Middleware\n200: \n201: **GIVEN** requests need structured logging  \n202: **WHEN** implementing request logging middleware  \n203: **THEN** LoggingMiddleware shall capture request details and response status\n204: \n205: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n206: \n207: ```go\n208: // Scenario 1: LoggingMiddleware struct definition\n209: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\n210: WHEN reading the LoggingMiddleware struct\n211: THEN it SHALL contain logger Logger field\n212: \n213: // Scenario 2: NewLoggingMiddleware constructor\n214: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\n215: WHEN calling NewLoggingMiddleware(logger Logger)\n216: THEN it SHALL return *LoggingMiddleware with logger field set\n217: \n218: // Scenario 3: Wrap method signature\n219: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\n220: WHEN reading the Wrap method\n221: THEN it SHALL have signature func(m *LoggingMiddleware) Wrap(next http.Handler) http.Handler\n222: \n223: // Scenario 4: Request logging fields\n224: GIVEN LoggingMiddleware wrapping a handler\n225: WHEN a request is processed\n226: THEN logger SHALL log: method, path, status, duration\n227: \n228: // Scenario 5: responseWriterWrapper captures status\n229: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go\n230: WHEN reading responseWriterWrapper struct\n231: THEN it SHALL embed http.ResponseWriter and capture status code field\n232: \n233: // Scenario 6: responseWriterWrapper.WriteHeader\n234: GIVEN a responseWriterWrapper instance\n235: WHEN WriteHeader(code int) is called\n236: THEN status field SHALL be set to code\n237: AND embedded ResponseWriter.WriteHeader SHALL be called\n238: ```\n239: \n240: ---\n241: \n242: ### REQ-007: Recovery Middleware\n243: \n244: **GIVEN** panics in handlers need to be recovered  \n245: **WHEN** implementing panic recovery middleware  \n246: **THEN** RecoveryMiddleware shall catch panics and return 500 response\n247: \n248: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n249: \n250: ```go\n251: // Scenario 1: RecoveryMiddleware struct definition\n252: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery.go\n253: WHEN reading the RecoveryMiddleware struct\n254: THEN it SHALL contain logger Logger field\n255: \n256: // Scenario 2: NewRecoveryMiddleware constructor\n257: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery.go\n258: WHEN calling NewRecoveryMiddleware(logger Logger)\n259: THEN it SHALL return *RecoveryMiddleware with logger field set\n260: \n261: // Scenario 3: Wrap method catches panic\n262: GIVEN RecoveryMiddleware wrapping a handler that panics\n263: WHEN the handler panics\n264: THEN panic SHALL be recovered\n265: AND logger SHALL log error with panic value and path\n266: AND response SHALL be HTTP 500 with body \"Internal Server Error\"\n267: \n268: // Scenario 4: Normal request passes through\n269: GIVEN RecoveryMiddleware wrapping a normal handler\n270: WHEN the handler does not panic\n271: THEN request SHALL pass through normally\n272: AND response SHALL be from the wrapped handler\n273: ```\n274: \n275: ---\n276: \n277: ### REQ-008: CORS Middleware\n278: \n279: **GIVEN** cross-origin requests need CORS headers  \n280: **WHEN** implementing CORS middleware  \n281: **THEN** CORSMiddleware shall add appropriate CORS headers and handle preflight\n282: \n283: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n284: \n285: ```go\n286: // Scenario 1: CORSMiddleware struct definition\n287: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors.go\n288: WHEN reading the CORSMiddleware struct\n289: THEN it SHALL contain config fields for allowed origins, methods, headers\n290: \n291: // Scenario 2: CORS headers added to response\n292: GIVEN CORSMiddleware wrapping a handler\n293: WHEN a request is processed\n294: THEN response SHALL include Access-Control-Allow-Origin header\n295: \n296: // Scenario 3: Preflight OPTIONS request\n297: GIVEN CORSMiddleware wrapping a handler\n298: WHEN OPTIONS request is sent\n299: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with CORS preflight headers\n300: AND Access-Control-Allow-Methods header SHALL be present\n301: AND Access-Control-Allow-Headers header SHALL be present\n302: \n303: // Scenario 4: NewCORSMiddleware constructor\n304: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors.go\n305: WHEN calling NewCORSMiddleware with allowed origins and methods\n306: THEN it SHALL return *CORSMiddleware with config fields set\n307: ```\n308: \n309: ---\n310: \n311: ### REQ-009: Request/Response Data Structures\n312: \n313: **GIVEN** API responses need unified JSON format  \n314: **WHEN** defining response data structures  \n315: **THEN** ErrorResponse and SuccessResponse shall be properly defined\n316: \n317: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n318: \n319: ```go\n320: // Scenario 1: ErrorResponse struct definition\n321: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\n322: WHEN reading the ErrorResponse struct\n323: THEN it SHALL contain fields: Code string with JSON tag \"code\", Message string with JSON tag \"message\", Details any with JSON tag \"details,omitempty\"\n324: \n325: // Scenario 2: SuccessResponse struct definition\n326: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\n327: WHEN reading the SuccessResponse struct\n328: THEN it SHALL contain field: Data any with JSON tag \"data\"\n329: \n330: // Scenario 3: ErrorResponse JSON serialization\n331: GIVEN an ErrorResponse with Code \"VALIDATION_ERROR\", Message \"Invalid parameter\", Details map[string]string{\"field\": \"name\"}\n332: WHEN marshaling to JSON\n333: THEN output SHALL be {\"code\":\"VALIDATION_ERROR\",\"message\":\"Invalid parameter\",\"details\":{\"field\":\"name\"}}\n334: \n335: // Scenario 4: SuccessResponse JSON serialization\n336: GIVEN a SuccessResponse with Data containing a map\n337: WHEN marshaling to JSON\n338: THEN output SHALL contain \"data\" key with the nested data\n339: ```\n340: \n341: ---\n342: \n343: ### REQ-010: Unified Error Handling\n344: \n345: **GIVEN** errors need unified HTTP response format  \n346: **WHEN** handling errors in handlers  \n347: **THEN** HandleError function shall map errors to correct HTTP status codes and JSON responses\n348: \n349: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n350: \n351: ```go\n352: // Scenario 1: HandleError function signature\n353: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\n354: WHEN reading HandleError function\n355: THEN it SHALL have signature func HandleError(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request, err error)\n356: \n357: // Scenario 2: Validation error response\n358: GIVEN HandleError called with validation error\n359: WHEN the error indicates invalid request\n360: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 400 with ErrorResponse Code \"VALIDATION_ERROR\"\n361: \n362: // Scenario 3: Not found error response\n363: GIVEN HandleError called with not found error\n364: WHEN the error indicates resource not found\n365: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 404 with ErrorResponse Code \"NOT_FOUND\"\n366: \n367: // Scenario 4: Internal error response\n368: GIVEN HandleError called with internal error\n369: WHEN the error is unexpected\n370: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 500 with ErrorResponse Code \"INTERNAL_ERROR\"\n371: \n372: // Scenario 5: Service unavailable error response\n373: GIVEN HandleError called with service unavailable error\n374: WHEN the error indicates dependency unavailable\n375: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 503 with ErrorResponse Code \"SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE\"\n376: \n377: // Scenario 6: ErrorResponse sets Content-Type\n378: GIVEN HandleError writes ErrorResponse\n379: WHEN writing response\n380: THEN Content-Type header SHALL be \"application/json\"\n381: ```\n382: \n383: ---\n384: \n385: ### REQ-011: Middleware Chain Order\n386: \n387: **GIVEN** middleware needs to execute in correct order  \n388: **WHEN** configuring middleware on the router  \n389: **THEN** middleware shall execute in the order: Recovery → Logging → CORS → Handler\n390: \n391: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n392: \n393: ```go\n394: // Scenario 1: Recovery executes first\n395: GIVEN middleware chain Recovery → Logging → Handler that panics\n396: WHEN handler panics\n397: THEN Recovery middleware SHALL catch panic before Logging logs\n398: \n399: // Scenario 2: Logging captures request duration\n400: GIVEN middleware chain Recovery → Logging → Handler\n401: WHEN request is processed\n402: THEN Logging SHALL capture full request duration including handler execution\n403: \n404: // Scenario 3: Middleware setup method\n405: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server.go\n406: WHEN reading setupMiddleware method\n407: THEN it SHALL apply middleware in correct order using chi.Use()\n408: \n409: // Scenario 4: CORS middleware optional\n410: GIVEN middleware configuration\n411: WHEN CORS middleware is not configured\n412: THEN CORS middleware SHALL NOT be applied to the chain\n413: ```\n414: \n415: ---\n416: \n417: ### REQ-012: Logger Interface\n418: \n419: **GIVEN** the server needs structured logging  \n420: **WHEN** defining logger abstraction  \n421: **THEN** Logger interface shall support Info and Error methods\n422: \n423: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n424: \n425: ```go\n426: // Scenario 1: Logger interface definition\n427: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types.go\n428: WHEN reading the Logger interface\n429: THEN it SHALL define Info(msg string, args ...any) method\n430: AND it SHALL define Error(msg string, args ...any) method\n431: \n432: // Scenario 2: Logger usage in HTTPServer\n433: GIVEN an HTTPServer instance\n434: WHEN logging events\n435: THEN logger.Info and logger.Error SHALL be used for structured logging\n436: \n437: // Scenario 3: Logger usage in middleware\n438: GIVEN LoggingMiddleware and RecoveryMiddleware\n439: WHEN logging request details or panics\n440: THEN logger SHALL be used for all log output\n441: ```\n442: \n443: ---\n444: \n445: ### REQ-013: Directory Structure\n446: \n447: **GIVEN** the module needs proper package structure  \n448: **WHEN** organizing code files  \n449: **THEN** files shall be organized according to the defined structure\n450: \n451: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n452: \n453: ```go\n454: // Scenario 1: Main package files\n455: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\n456: WHEN listing files\n457: THEN server.go, router.go, config.go, types.go SHALL exist\n458: \n459: // Scenario 2: Handlers directory\n460: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/\n461: WHEN listing files\n462: THEN handler.go and health.go SHALL exist\n463: \n464: // Scenario 3: Middleware directory\n465: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/\n466: WHEN listing files\n467: THEN logging.go, recovery.go, cors.go SHALL exist\n468: \n469: // Scenario 4: Package documentation\n470: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/doc.go\n471: WHEN reading the file\n472: THEN package-level godoc comment SHALL be present\n473: ```\n474: \n475: ---\n476: \n477: ### REQ-014: Unit Tests\n478: \n479: **GIVEN** the implementation needs test coverage  \n480: **WHEN** verifying functionality  \n481: **THEN** unit tests shall cover all core components\n482: \n483: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n484: \n485: ```go\n486: // Scenario 1: Types tests\n487: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/types_test.go\n488: WHEN running tests\n489: THEN HandleError tests SHALL verify correct JSON format and status codes\n490: AND SuccessResponse tests SHALL verify correct marshaling\n491: \n492: // Scenario 2: Server tests\n493: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/server_test.go\n494: WHEN running tests\n495: THEN NewHTTPServer tests SHALL verify default config\n496: AND Start/Stop tests SHALL verify lifecycle\n497: AND graceful shutdown tests SHALL verify context timeout handling\n498: \n499: // Scenario 3: Router tests\n500: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/router_test.go\n501: WHEN running tests\n502: THEN NewRouter tests SHALL verify router initialization\n503: AND RegisterHandlers tests SHALL verify multiple handler registration\n504: \n505: // Scenario 4: Health handler tests\n506: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health_test.go\n507: WHEN running tests\n508: THEN healthz test SHALL verify HTTP 200 with {\"status\": \"ok\"}\n509: AND readyz tests SHALL verify HTTP 200/503 based on IsReady()\n510: \n511: // Scenario 5: Logging middleware tests\n512: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging_test.go\n513: WHEN running tests\n514: THEN tests SHALL verify request method, path, status captured\n515: AND responseWriterWrapper tests SHALL verify status code capture\n516: \n517: // Scenario 6: Recovery middleware tests\n518: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery_test.go\n519: WHEN running tests\n520: THEN tests SHALL verify panic recovery\n521: AND tests SHALL verify HTTP 500 on panic\n522: \n523: // Scenario 7: CORS middleware tests\n524: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors_test.go\n525: WHEN running tests\n526: THEN tests SHALL verify Access-Control-Allow-Origin header\n527: AND tests SHALL verify OPTIONS preflight handling\n528: ```\n529: \n530: ---\n531: \n532: ### REQ-015: Integration Tests\n533: \n534: **GIVEN** the server needs end-to-end verification  \n535: **WHEN** testing with real HTTP requests  \n536: **THEN** integration tests shall verify complete request flow\n537: \n538: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n539: \n540: ```go\n541: // Scenario 1: End-to-end health check\n542: GIVEN a running HTTPServer on random port\n543: WHEN GET request sent to /healthz\n544: THEN response SHALL be HTTP 200 with correct JSON body\n545: \n546: // Scenario 2: End-to-end readiness check\n547: GIVEN a running HTTPServer on random port\n548: WHEN GET request sent to /readyz\n549: THEN response SHALL match HealthChecker state\n550: \n551: // Scenario 3: Middleware chain verification\n552: GIVEN a running HTTPServer with full middleware chain\n553: WHEN request is sent\n554: THEN middleware SHALL execute in correct order\n555: AND logging SHALL capture request details\n556: \n557: // Scenario 4: Panic recovery in integration\n558: GIVEN a running HTTPServer with endpoint that panics\n559: WHEN request is sent to panicking endpoint\n560: THEN server SHALL NOT crash\n561: AND response SHALL be HTTP 500\n562: ```\n563: \n564: ---\n565: \n566: ### REQ-016: Code Quality\n567: \n568: **GIVEN** the code needs to meet quality standards  \n569: **WHEN** running linting and validation  \n570: **THEN** code shall pass go vet and golangci-lint\n571: \n572: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n573: \n574: ```go\n575: // Scenario 1: go vet passes\n576: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\n577: WHEN running go vet ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\n578: THEN zero issues SHALL be reported\n579: \n580: // Scenario 2: golangci-lint passes\n581: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\n582: WHEN running golangci-lint run ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\n583: THEN zero linting issues SHALL be reported\n584: \n585: // Scenario 3: Build succeeds\n586: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\n587: WHEN running go build ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\n588: THEN build SHALL succeed without errors\n589: \n590: // Scenario 4: Test coverage threshold\n591: GIVEN pkg/workloadmanager/\n592: WHEN running go test -cover ./pkg/workloadmanager/...\n593: THEN coverage SHALL be greater than 80%\n594: ```\n595: \n596: ---\n597: \n598: ## Implementation Files\n599: \n600: | File | Purpose |\n601: |------|---------|\n602: | `pkg/workloadmanager/server.go` | HTTPServer implementation with lifecycle management |\n603: | `pkg/workloadmanager/router.go` | Router struct wrapping chi.Router |\n604: | `pkg/workloadmanager/config.go` | Config struct and DefaultConfig function |\n605: | `pkg/workloadmanager/types.go` | ErrorResponse, SuccessResponse, HandleError, Logger interface |\n606: | `pkg/workloadmanager/doc.go` | Package-level documentation |\n607: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/handler.go` | Handler interface and HandlerFunc type |\n608: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go` | HealthHandler and HealthChecker interface |\n609: | `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging.go` | LoggingMiddleware and responseWriterWrapper |\n610: | `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery.go` | RecoveryMiddleware |\n611: | `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors.go` | CORSMiddleware |\n612: | `pkg/workloadmanager/server_test.go` | HTTPServer unit tests |\n613: | `pkg/workloadmanager/router_test.go` | Router unit tests |\n614: | `pkg/workloadmanager/types_test.go` | Types and HandleError unit tests |\n615: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health_test.go` | HealthHandler unit tests |\n616: | `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/logging_test.go` | LoggingMiddleware unit tests |\n617: | `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/recovery_test.go` | RecoveryMiddleware unit tests |\n618: | `pkg/workloadmanager/middleware/cors_test.go` | CORSMiddleware unit tests |\n619: | `pkg/workloadmanager/integration_test.go` | End-to-end integration tests |\n620: \n621: ---\n622: \n623: ## Dependencies\n624: \n625: | Package | Purpose |\n626: |---------|---------|\n627: | `net/http` | Standard library HTTP server |\n628: | `context` | Request context for graceful shutdown |\n629: | `sync` | Concurrency control |\n630: | `os/signal` | Signal handling for graceful shutdown |\n631: | `time` | Timeout configuration |\n632: | `encoding/json` | JSON serialization for responses |\n633: | `github.com/go-chi/chi/v5` | Lightweight HTTP router |\n634: \n635: ---\n636: \n637: ## API Endpoints\n638: \n639: | Endpoint | Method | Purpose |\n640: |----------|--------|---------|\n641: | `/healthz` | GET | Kubernetes liveness probe |\n642: | `/readyz` | GET | Kubernetes readiness probe |\n643: \n644: ---\n645: \n646: ## Error Codes\n647: \n648: | Code | HTTP Status | Description |\n649: |------|-------------|-------------|\n650: | `VALIDATION_ERROR` | 400 | Invalid request parameter |\n651: | `NOT_FOUND` | 404 | Resource not found |\n652: | `INTERNAL_ERROR` | 500 | Unexpected server error |\n653: | `SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE` | 503 | Dependency unavailable |\n654: \n655: ---\n656: \n657: ## Validation Checklist\n658: \n659: - [ ] HTTPServer supports graceful startup and shutdown\n660: - [ ] Router framework supports route grouping with chi\n661: - [ ] Middleware chain executes in correct order\n662: - [ ] Health endpoints `/healthz` and `/readyz` respond correctly\n663: - [ ] Error responses use unified JSON format\n664: - [ ] Pass `go vet` with zero issues\n665: - [ ] Pass `golangci-lint` with zero issues\n666: - [ ] Unit tests pass with >80% coverage\n667: - [ ] Integration tests pass\n668: - [ ] All exported types have godoc comments\n\n(End of file - total 668 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP 服务框架\n\nModule: `pkg/workloadmanager`  \nLanguage: Go  \nSize: M\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nDefine the HTTP service framework for WorkloadManager, providing RESTful API infrastructure, middleware architecture, lifecycle management, health endpoints, and unified error handling.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### REQ-001: HTTPServer Configuration\n\n**GIVEN** the `server.go` file defines the HTTP server core implementation  \n**WHEN** a developer needs to configure and manage the HTTP server lifecycle  ","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775850780899,"end":1775850780909}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775850780923,"sessionID":"ses_2870bf392ffeKZ8jL8UQ3Wxavm","part":{"id":"prt_d78f46378001zMAEEiB7el6l4D","messageID":"msg_d78f448fa001eBkQbOFsCzcwIv","sessionID":"ses_2870bf392ffeKZ8jL8UQ3Wxavm","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-eb52d410d4c34433b72a4ae7bbab99a9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/session_manager.go"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/session_manager.go</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: package router\n2: \n3: import (\n4: \t\"bytes\"\n5: \t\"context\"\n6: \t\"encoding/json\"\n7: \t\"fmt\"\n8: \t\"io\"\n9: \t\"net/http\"\n10: \t\"os\"\n11: \t\"strings\"\n12: \t\"time\"\n13: \n14: \t\"github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types\"\n15: \t\"golang.org/x/net/http2\"\n16: )\n17: \n18: type sessionManager struct {\n19: \tstoreClient     Store\n20: \tworkloadMgrAddr string\n21: \thttpClient      *http.Client\n22: }\n23: \n24: func NewSessionManager(storeClient Store) (SessionManager, error) {\n25: \tworkloadMgrAddr := os.Getenv(\"WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL\")\n26: \tif workloadMgrAddr == \"\" {\n27: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL environment variable is required\")\n28: \t}\n29: \n30: \ttransport := &http.Transport{\n31: \t\tMaxIdleConnsPerHost: 100,\n32: \t\tDisableCompression:  false,\n33: \t}\n34: \n35: \thttp2.ConfigureTransport(transport)\n36: \n37: \thttpClient := &http.Client{\n38: \t\tTimeout:   2 * time.Minute,\n39: \t\tTransport: transport,\n40: \t}\n41: \n42: \treturn &sessionManager{\n43: \t\tstoreClient:     storeClient,\n44: \t\tworkloadMgrAddr: workloadMgrAddr,\n45: \t\thttpClient:      httpClient,\n46: \t}, nil\n47: }\n48: \n49: func (m *sessionManager) GetSandboxBySession(ctx context.Context, sessionID string, namespace string, name string, kind string) (*types.SandboxInfo, error) {\n50: \tif sessionID == \"\" {\n51: \t\treturn m.createSandbox(ctx, namespace, name, kind)\n52: \t}\n53: \n54: \tsandbox, err := m.storeClient.GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID)\n55: \tif err != nil {\n56: \t\treturn nil, &SessionNotFoundError{SessionID: sessionID}\n57: \t}\n58: \n59: \treturn sandbox, nil\n60: }\n61: \n62: func (m *sessionManager) createSandbox(ctx context.Context, namespace string, name string, kind string) (*types.SandboxInfo, error) {\n63: \treqBody := types.CreateSandboxRequest{\n64: \t\tKind:      kind,\n65: \t\tName:      name,\n66: \t\tNamespace: namespace,\n67: \t}\n68: \n69: \tif err := reqBody.Validate(); err != nil {\n70: \t\treturn nil, err\n71: \t}\n72: \n73: \tvar endpoint string\n74: \tswitch kind {\n75: \tcase types.AgentRuntimeKind:\n76: \t\tendpoint = m.workloadMgrAddr + \"/v1/agent-runtime\"\n77: \tcase types.CodeInterpreterKind:\n78: \t\tendpoint = m.workloadMgrAddr + \"/v1/code-interpreter\"\n79: \tdefault:\n80: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported kind: %s\", kind)\n81: \t}\n82: \n83: \tbodyBytes, err := json.Marshal(reqBody)\n84: \tif err != nil {\n85: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to marshal request: %w\", err)\n86: \t}\n87: \n88: \treq, err := http.NewRequestWithContext(ctx, http.MethodPost, endpoint, bytes.NewReader(bodyBytes))\n89: \tif err != nil {\n90: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to create request: %w\", err)\n91: \t}\n92: \n93: \treq.Header.Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n94: \n95: \tsaToken, err := readServiceAccountToken()\n96: \tif err == nil && saToken != \"\" {\n97: \t\treq.Header.Set(\"Authorization\", \"Bearer \"+saToken)\n98: \t}\n99: \n100: \tresp, err := m.httpClient.Do(req)\n101: \tif err != nil {\n102: \t\treturn nil, &WorkloadManagerError{\n103: \t\t\tStatusCode: http.StatusInternalServerError,\n104: \t\t\tMsg:        fmt.Sprintf(\"failed to connect to workload manager: %v\", err),\n105: \t\t}\n106: \t}\n107: \tdefer resp.Body.Close()\n108: \n109: \trespBody, err := io.ReadAll(resp.Body)\n110: \tif err != nil {\n111: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to read response: %w\", err)\n112: \t}\n113: \n114: \tif resp.StatusCode != http.StatusOK {\n115: \t\treturn nil, &WorkloadManagerError{\n116: \t\t\tStatusCode: resp.StatusCode,\n117: \t\t\tMsg:        string(respBody),\n118: \t\t}\n119: \t}\n120: \n121: \tvar createResp types.CreateSandboxResponse\n122: \tif err := json.Unmarshal(respBody, &createResp); err != nil {\n123: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to parse response: %w\", err)\n124: \t}\n125: \n126: \tif createResp.SessionID == \"\" {\n127: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"empty sessionId in response\")\n128: \t}\n129: \n130: \tsandbox := &types.SandboxInfo{\n131: \t\tKind:             kind,\n132: \t\tSandboxID:        createResp.SandboxID,\n133: \t\tSandboxNamespace: IdentityNamespace,\n134: \t\tSandboxName:      createResp.SandboxName,\n135: \t\tName:             name,\n136: \t\tSessionID:        createResp.SessionID,\n137: \t\tCreatedAt:        time.Now(),\n138: \t\tExpiresAt:        time.Now().Add(30 * time.Minute),\n139: \t\tStatus:           \"Running\",\n140: \t\tEntryPoints:      createResp.EntryPoints,\n141: \t}\n142: \n143: \tif err := m.storeClient.StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox); err != nil {\n144: \t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to store sandbox: %w\", err)\n145: \t}\n146: \n147: \treturn sandbox, nil\n148: }\n149: \n150: func readServiceAccountToken() (string, error) {\n151: \ttokenPath := \"/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token\"\n152: \tdata, err := os.ReadFile(tokenPath)\n153: \tif err != nil {\n154: \t\treturn \"\", err\n155: \t}\n156: \treturn strings.TrimSpace(string(data)), nil\n157: }\n\n(End of file - total 157 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"package router\n\nimport (\n\t\"bytes\"\n\t\"context\"\n\t\"encoding/json\"\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"io\"\n\t\"net/http\"\n\t\"os\"\n\t\"strings\"\n\t\"time\"\n\n\t\"github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types\"\n\t\"golang.org/x/net/http2\"\n)\n\ntype sessionManager struct {\n\tstoreClient     Store\n\tworkloadMgrAddr string","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/session_manager.go","time":{"start":1775850780894,"end":1775850780922}}}}
